00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:14.530
We have a very full
house here today.

00:00:14.530 --> 00:00:17.020
Thank you all for joining us.

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:19.740
I'm very much looking forward
to our discussion, "The Museum,

00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:21.840
the City, and the University."

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.890
Our program today reflects
Radcliffe's dual mission

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:30.060
to support scholars, scientists,
and artists as they pursue

00:00:30.060 --> 00:00:32.780
innovative research
and creative work,

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:36.570
and to share the fruits of those
endeavors with the wide public

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:39.270
through lectures,
conferences, exhibitions.

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:42.870
And discussions like
today's I am excited to dive

00:00:42.870 --> 00:00:46.080
into what I know will be
a fascinating discussion

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:50.370
about the present and future of
three institutions that matter

00:00:50.370 --> 00:00:54.270
a great deal to me, and I
would guess to many of you

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:55.560
in this room--

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.570
the art museum, the
university, and the city.

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:01.620
To guide us, we are
fortunate to have

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:04.950
five leaders of Boston's
major art museums,

00:01:04.950 --> 00:01:07.680
as well as our distinguished
moderator, Harvard

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:10.910
and Radcliffe's own
professor Yukio Lippit.

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:14.810
Museums and universities have
distinctive but overlapping

00:01:14.810 --> 00:01:17.360
missions in today's society.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:20.270
Both are committed to
preserving cultural knowledge

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:23.240
in abstract and material form.

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:27.870
Both are dedicated to advancing
new knowledge, new research.

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:30.920
And they share a common
mission to communicate

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:35.270
ideas and aesthetic appreciation
in a variety of ways

00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:37.700
to broad constituencies.

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:42.360
These links between museums
and universities are not new.

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:44.870
They have a long history.

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:47.780
When Western European
nations were first forming

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:51.230
and monarchs were
consolidating their power,

00:01:51.230 --> 00:01:53.630
universities and
lavish collections

00:01:53.630 --> 00:01:57.350
of art and antiquities played
important and complementary

00:01:57.350 --> 00:01:59.420
roles in their societies.

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:01.620
Teaching and
research universities

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:04.490
helped solidify
national identities,

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:07.400
and royal collections
glorified the crown

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:09.889
and conferred legitimacy.

00:02:09.889 --> 00:02:13.160
Both also preserved the
ideological and material

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:16.970
culture of their
patrons for the future.

00:02:16.970 --> 00:02:20.660
In the 18th and 19th centuries,
when many of the major museums

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:24.980
we know today emerged as
important cultural institutions

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:27.440
in cities around
the world, they took

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:31.670
on important societal objectives
and engaged a much broader

00:02:31.670 --> 00:02:32.900
public.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.000
Not only did their
collecting and research

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.410
commitments expand, but as
democratic government took hold

00:02:39.410 --> 00:02:42.380
in the Western world,
museums aspired

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.070
to use their cultural
treasures to cultivate

00:02:46.070 --> 00:02:48.140
enlightened citizens.

00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:51.680
Here in the United States, the
19th and early 20th centuries

00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:55.400
also saw massive immigration
to Boston, New York,

00:02:55.400 --> 00:02:57.230
and other major cities.

00:02:57.230 --> 00:03:00.200
The Boston Museum of Fine Arts
and the Metropolitan Museum

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:03.830
of Art in New York,
both founded in 1870,

00:03:03.830 --> 00:03:07.040
aimed to serve as
Americanizing institutions

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:09.950
in urban centers
that were exploding

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:12.560
in size and population.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:17.420
Much has changed, of course,
between the 1870s and today.

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:21.260
But deep connections live
on between national identity

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:24.260
and collections of
visual material culture,

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:28.100
between museums and universities
as preservers and promoters

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:32.420
of new knowledge, and between
museums and their publics.

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:35.300
To highlight one
very recent example,

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:38.990
earlier this year, our five
panelists wrote an open letter

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:42.050
eloquently defending the
National Arts and Humanities

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:45.770
endowments and articulating
their shared belief,

00:03:45.770 --> 00:03:48.470
and I quote, that
"access to the arts

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:52.500
is at the core of a democratic
and equitable society."

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:54.230
End quote.

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:58.100
These issues have taken on
greater urgency and importance

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:00.920
in recent years and even months.

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:04.130
We are watching as public
support for the arts

00:04:04.130 --> 00:04:07.880
and humanities is
increasingly contested.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:11.510
We are experiencing a new
wave of nativism and pressures

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:13.880
for Americanization
that surely have

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:18.589
implications for the missions of
universities and museums alike.

00:04:18.589 --> 00:04:22.540
And as American cities
struggle for economic survival,

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:24.890
their museums face
pressures to be

00:04:24.890 --> 00:04:27.050
engines of growth
and development,

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:30.080
in addition to their
traditional roles in education

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:35.090
and research, potentially
leading to conflicting agendas.

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:37.610
Finally, current
political realities

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:40.520
make museums' efforts to
engage the public in the arts

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:44.870
and humanities both more
important and potentially more

00:04:44.870 --> 00:04:47.690
difficult than ever before.

00:04:47.690 --> 00:04:50.480
I am grateful that we have
with us this afternoon

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:53.960
such a distinguished panel
to help us explore and better

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:58.580
understand some of these issues,
and surely others as well.

00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:01.250
Before I hand things
over to Yukio Lippit,

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:04.370
let me invite you all to
continue the conversation

00:05:04.370 --> 00:05:07.400
with our panelists and with
each other at a reception

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:10.940
immediately following this
program right next door at Fay

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:12.020
House.

